  "summary": "After reading a newspaper headline regarding the sudden collapse and impending scandals of the firm Hobson, Jekyll, and Lucas, Theodora Darrel informs Vincent Easton that her husband, Richard, is associated with the company. Despite Vincent's attempts to dissuade her from returning to her marriage, Theodora insists on going back to Richard because the company's bankruptcy threatens to ruin him. Vincent reacts with anger, hurling venomous words at her to cause her pain, but Theodora remains silent and leaves him to say goodbye.\n\nTheodora arrives at the Darrells' house in Chelsea and finds Richard in a worn-out state. He informs her that despite the crisis, she retains her legal right to live in their house. While Richard attempts to comfort her and claims things will improve, Theodora senses he is withholding information. As Richard falls asleep with his head on her knees, she remains suspicious of his secrecy.\n\nThree days later, Theodora confronts Richard about the details of his situation. Richard initially deflects her questions, claiming the matters are too complex for women to understand. He eventually admits that while his actions regarding a large property deal in South Africa were morally just, they may be legally problematic and could lead to criminal charges. As Richard attempts to defend himself with long-winded explanations, Theodora observes his nervous behavior and realizes he is concealing the full truth. Under the pressure of the discussion and Theodora's contemptuous glances, Richard breaks down and buries his head in his hands.",
